The Drake Equation is a probabilistic argument used to estimate the number of active, communicative extraterrestrial civilizations in the Milky Way galaxy. The equation is:

N = R* • fp • ne • fl • fi • fc • L

where:
N = the number of civilizations in our galaxy with which communication might be possible;
R* = the average rate of star formation in our galaxy;
fp = the fraction of those stars that have planetary systems;
ne = the average number of planets that can potentially support life per star that has planets;
fl = the fraction of planets that could support life that actually develop life at some point;
fi = the fraction of planets with life that actually go on to develop intelligent life (civilizations);
fc = the fraction of civilizations that develop a technology that releases detectable signs of their existence into space;
L = the length of time for which such civilizations release detectable signals into space.

Estimates for these parameters vary widely based on different assumptions, and many are highly uncertain. Here are some rough estimates:

1. R* = 1-3 new stars per year (pretty certain)
2. fp = 0.2-0.5 (20-50% of stars have planets, based on Kepler mission data)
3. ne = 1-5 (highly uncertain, depends on what you consider "potentially habitable")
4. fl = 0.1-1 (10-100% chance that life develops on a habitable planet, highly uncertain)
5. fi = 0.01-1 (1-100% chance that life develops intelligence, highly uncertain)
6. fc = 0.01-0.1 (1-10% chance that intelligent life develops detectable technology, highly uncertain)
7. L = 100-10,000 years (highly uncertain, depends on how long a civilization can survive)

If we take the lower estimates for each parameter, we get N = 1 * 0.2 * 1 * 0.1 * 0.01 * 0.01 * 100 = 0.0002 civilizations.

If we take the higher estimates for each parameter, we get N = 3 * 0.5 * 5 * 1 * 1 * 0.1 * 10,000 = 750,000 civilizations.

So, based on these rough estimates, the number of detectable civilizations in our galaxy could range from virtually none to hundreds of thousands. This wide range reflects the great uncertainty in many of the parameters.

